					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8673179#post-4062012</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8673179/scp-1037#post-4062012</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sun, 18 Nov 2018 16:07:06 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>dankaar</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1790336</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>According to the article's history, is was contained in rubber. Could have been synthetic rubber.</p> <p>Then again, synthetic rubber is made from petroleum byproducts. It's a stretch, but you could argue that anything made from petroleum <em>is</em> a biological material, since the oil likely started off as a giant mat of algae, even if it is processed to the point of being incredibly toxic to most biological organisms.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8673179#post-4061986</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8673179/scp-1037#post-4061986</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sun, 18 Nov 2018 15:35:55 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>PMEase-G4</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>4207957</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>But SCP-1037 only affects non-biological material, so given that the Sarkics make <strong>everything</strong> from organic material, it would have no effect on them, right? Or am I missing something here?</p> <p>Based on its effect I would have assumed that it was used as a weapon <em>against</em> the Church of the Broken God and its mechanical creations and not as a weapon created by them to fight the Sarkics.</p> <p>And now that I think about it, how does it affect the gelatin in which it was originally contained? Gelatin is made from animal skin and bones and should therefore not be affected by SCP-1037, if it only affect non-biological materials.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
